# Cloudflare Workers — Cohort-Based Deployments Explained

A plain-english breakdown of cohort-based deployments in Cloudflare Workers,
covering every concept from scratch.

-----

## What problem does this solve?

Normal gradual deployments send a random percentage of traffic to a new version.
The same user might hit v1 one request and v2 the next. That’s unpredictable.

Cohort deployments let you say: **specific groups of users always get a specific version.**

```
Normal gradual deployment:
  All traffic
    ├── 90% ──► v1 (stable)
    └── 10% ──► v2 (new)   ← random, any user could land here

Cohort deployment:
  All traffic
    ├── No cohort (default) ──► 100% v1
    ├── "canary" cohort     ──► 100% v2
    └── "enterprise" cohort ──► 100% v1   ← pinned, never random
```

-----

## Key concepts

### Versions array

A list of which Worker versions exist and what % of traffic goes to each:

```json
"versions": [
  { "version_id": "abc123-stable", "percentage": 90 },
  { "version_id": "def456-new",    "percentage": 10 }
]
```

Every cohort has its own independent versions array. Percentages within each must sum to 100.

### Cohorts array

A list of named groups, each with their own versions array:

```json
"cohorts": [
  {
    "name": "canary",
    "versions": [
      { "version_id": "abc123-stable", "percentage": 50 },
      { "version_id": "def456-new",    "percentage": 50 }
    ]
  },
  {
    "name": "ent",
    "versions": [
      { "version_id": "abc123-stable", "percentage": 100 }
    ]
  }
]
```

Cohorts are completely independent — changing canary’s split doesn’t affect ent or the default.

-----

## How routing works (decision tree)

Every incoming request goes through this flow:

```
Incoming request
        │
        ▼
Has Cloudflare-Workers-Version-Overrides header?
  YES ──► use that exact version. done. skip everything else.
  NO
        │
        ▼
Has Cloudflare-Workers-Cohort header matching a cohort name?
  YES ──► use that cohort's versions array
  NO  ──► use the default versions array
        │
        ▼
Has Cloudflare-Workers-Version-Key header?
  YES ──► deterministic hash pick from the chosen versions array (sticky)
  NO  ──► random weighted pick from the chosen versions array
```

### The three headers explained simply

|Header                                |What it does                              |Who uses it             |
|--------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|------------------------|
|`Cloudflare-Workers-Version-Overrides`|Skip all routing, go to this exact version|Developers / QA testing |
|`Cloudflare-Workers-Cohort`           |Use this cohort’s versions array          |Your infra / Worker code|
|`Cloudflare-Workers-Version-Key`      |Always pick the same version for this key |Session consistency     |

**Priority order:** Override > Cohort > Default. More specific always wins.

-----

## What is the Version-Overrides header?

A “master key” for developers to force a specific version, bypassing all routing rules:

```sh
curl https://example.com \
  -H 'Cloudflare-Workers-Version-Overrides: def456-new-version'
```

Cloudflare finds that version ID anywhere in your deployment (default or any cohort)
and routes directly to it. Used internally by devs and QA — never by real users.

-----

## What is the Version-Key header / sticky sessions?

**The problem:** A user makes a request, hits v2, fills out half a form.
Next request randomly hits v1. v1 doesn’t know about their form. Things break.

**Sticky session** = same user always hits the same version, every request.

**How it works:**

```
Cloudflare-Workers-Version-Key: user_12345

Cloudflare hashes "user_12345" → always produces the same version pick

user_12345 ──► hash ──► always v1
user_67890 ──► hash ──► always v2
```

You set this to a user ID or session ID. Only needed when you have a percentage
split AND need consistency. If a cohort is already 100% one version, you don’t need it.

