## Two ways to assign cohorts to requests

### Way 1 — Gateway Entrypoint Pattern (Worker figures it out in code)

Your Worker reads the request, looks up the user in your database, decides the cohort,
then calls itself again with the cohort attached.

```
Request arrives (no cohort info)
        │
        ▼
export default runs (front door)
  reads account ID from request
  calls database: "what plan is this user?"
  database says: "enterprise"
  cohort = "ent"
        │
        │  ctx.exports.Service({ version: { cohort: "ent" } })
        ▼
Cloudflare boots a fresh invocation on the "ent" version
        │
        ▼
export class Service runs (does the actual work)
on the correct version ✅
```

**Why the two-step with ctx.exports.Service?**

`export default` is already running on some version when it figures out the cohort.
You can’t change versions mid-execution. So it hands off to a second entrypoint,
telling Cloudflare the cohort BEFORE that second invocation boots — so it starts
on the right version from the beginning.

```
export default  = detective. only job is to figure out the cohort. no real work.
export Service  = does the actual work. always runs on the correct version.
```

**The code:**

```ts
import { WorkerEntrypoint } from "cloudflare:workers";

// Front door — figures out cohort, hands off
export default {
  async fetch(request, env, ctx) {
    const accountId = request.headers.get("cf-account-id");

    const cohort = accountId
      ? resolveCohortFromAccountId(request, env, accountId)
      : resolveCohortFromUrl(request, env);

    return ctx.exports.Service({ version: { cohort } }).handle(request);
  }
};

// Cohort resolution logic — your business rules
function resolveCohortFromAccountId(request, env, accountId) {
  const plan = lookupAccountPlan(accountId, env);

  if (isEmployee(request))    return "employee";
  if (plan === "free")        return "free";
  if (plan === "enterprise")  return "ent";
  return "paid";
}

// Fallback — resolve from URL if no account ID
function resolveCohortFromUrl(request, env) {
  const url = new URL(request.url);
  const hostname = url.hostname;
  const accountMatch = hostname.match(/^([a-f0-9]+)\.r2\.cloudflarestorage\.com$/i);

  if (!accountMatch) return "ent"; // safe default
  const accountId = accountMatch[1];
  const plan = lookupAccountPlan(accountId, env);

  if (plan === "free") return "free";
  return "paid";
}

// Side door — does the actual work on the correct version
export class Service extends WorkerEntrypoint {
  async handle(request) {
    // your real Worker logic goes here
  }
}
```

**Required in wrangler.toml:**

```toml
compatibility_flags = ["enable_ctx_exports"]
```

**When to use this:** When cohort logic requires your database or app knowledge.
The request has no cohort info — your Worker figures it all out internally.

-----

### Way 2 — External Cohort Header (something upstream labels the request)

The `Cloudflare-Workers-Cohort` header is set BEFORE the request reaches your Worker.
Your Worker code doesn’t need any special logic — routing happens at the infra level.

#### Option A: Client sets it directly (testing only)

```sh
curl https://example.com -H 'Cloudflare-Workers-Cohort: canary'
```

Never use this in production — anyone can fake their cohort.

#### Option B: Cloudflare Transform Rule (no code changes)

The client makes a normal request with a cookie. A Transform Rule reads the cookie
and adds the cohort header automatically.

```
Browser sends:
  Cookie: session=abc123; cohort=canary; theme=dark

Transform Rule runs:
  reads cookie → extracts "canary" → adds header

Your Worker receives:
  Cookie: session=abc123; cohort=canary; theme=dark
  Cloudflare-Workers-Cohort: canary   ← Cloudflare added this
```

Dashboard setup:

```
Rules → Transform Rules → Create rule

IF:    http.cookie contains "cohort="
THEN:  Set dynamic request header
       Name:  Cloudflare-Workers-Cohort
       Value: regex_replace(http.cookie, ".*cohort=([^;]+).*", "${1}")
```

How the cookie gets there in the first place — your login endpoint sets it:

```js
// when user logs in on your backend
const plan = await getUserPlan(user.id);
const cohort = plan === "enterprise" ? "ent" : "canary";

response.headers.set("Set-Cookie",
  `cohort=${cohort}; Path=/; Max-Age=2592000; HttpOnly`
);
```

Now every request from that browser automatically carries the cohort cookie.

#### Option C: Upstream “bouncer” Worker (most secure)

A separate Worker authenticates the user, decides their cohort from trusted
server-side data, and stamps the header before forwarding.

```
User request (no header, or spoofed header)
        │
        ▼
Auth Worker (bouncer)
  authenticates user
  looks up real plan
  overwrites header with correct cohort
        │
        ▼
Main Worker
  receives trustworthy Cloudflare-Workers-Cohort header
  routes to correct version ✅
```

```js
// auth Worker
export default {
  async fetch(request, env) {
    const user = await authenticateUser(request);
    const cohort = user.isBetaTester ? "canary" : "ent";

    // clone request (Request objects are immutable — can't modify in place)
    const modifiedRequest = new Request(request, {
      headers: new Headers(request.headers)
    });
    modifiedRequest.headers.set("Cloudflare-Workers-Cohort", cohort);

    return env.DOWNSTREAM_SERVICE.fetch(modifiedRequest);
  }
};
```

wrangler.toml for auth Worker:

```toml
[[services]]
binding = "DOWNSTREAM_SERVICE"
service = "your-main-worker-name"
```

