## Making it reliable in production

### Always default to your safest version

```js
function resolveCohort(request, user) {
  if (!user)                  return "ent"; // not logged in → safest default
  if (user.plan === "enterprise") return "ent";
  if (user.isBetaTester)      return "canary";
  return "free";
}
```

When in doubt, give users the stable version — not the experimental one.

### Wrap database lookups in try/catch

```js
async function resolveCohort(accountId, env) {
  try {
    const plan = await lookupAccountPlan(accountId, env);
    if (plan === "enterprise") return "ent";
    return "paid";
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("cohort lookup failed:", error);
    return "ent"; // fail safe — never fail open to canary
  }
}
```

### Make sure your default versions array is also your stable version

Even if all cohort routing fails completely, requests fall back to the default.
Make sure that default also points to stable, not canary:

```json
"versions": [
  { "version_id": "abc123-stable", "percentage": 100 }
]
```

