## Limitations to know about

|Limit                                          |Value                             |
|-----------------------------------------------|----------------------------------|
|Max cohorts per deployment                     |5                                 |
|Max unique version IDs across entire deployment|2                                 |
|Max cohort name length                         |10 characters                     |
|Allowed characters in cohort name              |Alphanumeric, hyphens, underscores|

**The 2 unique version ID limit** means you can have 5 cohorts but they all have
to reference the same 2 versions. You can split traffic between those 2 versions
differently per cohort, but you can’t introduce a 3rd distinct version anywhere.

**Service bindings** — cohort routing doesn’t propagate. If your Worker calls
another Worker via a service binding, that second Worker uses its own deployment
config independently. The cohort header is not forwarded automatically.

**Durable Objects** — completely ignore cohort headers. They follow their own
versioning rules based on when they were first created.

**Runtime fallback** — if the cohort header value doesn’t match any defined cohort,
the request silently falls back to the default versions array. No error is thrown.
This is why logging `ctx.version.cohort` matters — misconfigurations won’t surface
as errors, they’ll just silently misroute.

